    <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
      <head>Biographical History</head>
      <p>Rollin Crampton (1886-1970) was an American painter and illustrator known for his geometric abstractions.</p>
      <p>Born in New Haven, Connecticut, Crampton studied at Yale University School of Fine Arts and won a scholarship from 
	  the Art Student's League.  In 1936 he was appointed mural supervisor for the New York City Art Project.  He was the recipient 
	  of two Purchase Prizes (SUNY New Paltz and Lousiana State University); his work was exhibited at museums and galleries 
	  across the country (including the Museum of Modern Art) and is in the permanent collections of the Whitney Museum of American 
	  Art and the Albright Gallery.</p>
    </bioghist>
    <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
      <head>Scope and Contents of the Collection</head>
      <p>The 
        
        <emph render="bold">Rollin Crampton Papers</emph> consist of biographical material, correspondence, subject files, manuscripts, and published 
	  material.</p>
      <p>
        <emph render="bold">Biographical material</emph> contains a biographical sketch by Crampton for the Program Director of 
	  the Longview Foundation.</p>
      <p>
        <emph render="bold">Correspondence</emph> is incoming only; the majority are photostats, not originals.  Included in the 
	  photostats are letters from art critic Clement Greenberg and artist Jackson Pollock.</p>
      <p>
        <emph render="bold">Subject files</emph> contains exhibit notices, a genealogy of Mrs. Crampton, and photographs of 
	  Crampton, his work, and others.</p>
      <p>
        <emph render="bold">Manuscripts</emph> contains a one-page manuscript entitled "Laws of proportion."</p>
      <p>
        <emph render="bold">Published material</emph> consists of a newspaper and magazine clippings about Crampton and his work.</p>
    </scopecontent>
    <arrangement encodinganalog="351$a">
